  "text": "McGlinchey et al. considered the possibility that the different rooms used for the role-play and for conditional discrimination training inadvertently established a significant role for contextual cues [CITATION_1] in the control of responding. To test this suggestion they arranged explicit contextual cues in the role-play (\"W\" and \"Z\"). Subjects were a girl aged 8 years and a young woman aged 24 years. Stimulus presentations and equivalence training procedures were the same as those used previously. The role-play, however, began with the instruction to place items of clothing on themselves in the presence of one of two objects (\"W\" or \"Z\").",
